Explanation:

- The store method in CommentController returns response()->turboStream([...]) and its declared return type is MultiplePendingTurboStreamResponse. That indicates a successful response is an HTTP 200 with Turbo Stream payload (MIME type used by Turbo Streams is typically text/vnd.turbo-stream.html) containing multiple <turbo-stream> fragments (prepend, replace, update).
- Validation is handled by CommentsRequest (a FormRequest). If validation fails, Laravel returns a 422 Unprocessable Entity with a JSON payload describing validation errors.
- Authentication is required (the code uses Auth::user()). If the caller is not authenticated the typical responses are an authentication failure â€” in many Laravel apps this is a 401 (API) or a redirect (web). For an API-style spec include 401 Unauthorized.
- No explicit 201 or other success codes are returned by this controller, so the success response is modeled as 200 OK with Turbo Stream content.
- I will provide three response objects: 200 (Turbo Stream), 422 (validation errors), and 401 (unauthenticated). Each response object contains a description and an example payload (examples keyed by MIME type), and no $ref.

